take powerful drugs to suppress their immune system to prevent rejection. T=
hat&#8217;s clearly not ideal.</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb=
(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">Sana has developed a way t=
o modify donor insulin-producing cells (called HIP technology) so they can =
"hide" from the immune system.</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb=
(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">The transplanted cells pro=
duced insulin, as evidenced by C-peptide levels, and avoided immune rejecti=
on, meaning the transplanted cells successfully functioned like natural ins=
ulin-producing beta cells. Further more, the cells properly transplanted wi=
thout the need for potentially harmful immunosuppressive drugs.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26px;font-size: =
16px;">This kind of cell transplant could completely change how we treat ty=
pe 1 diabetes by offering a long-term solution without daily insulin shots =
or risky immune-suppressing drugs. Additionally, it shows that we might be =
able to transplant cells or organs without the body attacking them, which c=
ould transform how we treat all kinds of diseases.</p><p style=3D"margin: 0=
 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><span>=
